metadata.name: The Samsara-Verse #3
metadata.description:
Samsara is the endless Wheel of Life, where uncountable numbers of souls ceaselessly wander through its 6 realms - Deva-gati (abode of the gods), Asura-gati (demi-gods), Preta-gati (hungry ghosts), Naraka-gati (Hell), Tiryagyoni-gati (animals), Manusya-gati (the human realm).
 
These realms are interleaved with manifold planes of existence separated by the thinnest of veils.
And yet - these hives of endless activity are but a small fraction of the totality of the metaverse, as multitudes of unformed universes, as yet mere sketches, await their blooming.

This artwork consists of both a visual aspect and a sonic representation echoing the voices of the denizens of the various planes of the Samsara-Verse.

Once the piece has finished drawing, click or press "m" to unmute the soundtrack.
Press "s" to save the image as a ".png" file (4800x3600 pixels).

Collaborative work by Geoffrey Crayon - art design and coding - and Cylonix (JJClark) - sound design. The audio samples used (in addition to generative drones) are from Loopology and Splice.

metadata.name: Inland Emotions #38
metadata.description:
Inland Emotions

Over the centuries, ancient philosophers and modern psychologists have come to the same basic conclusion. The fact is that, according to a few millennia of research, there are a limited number of distinct human emotions, predefined by the human psyche. Sometimes it may seem like we are experiencing a "new" one, but on closer inspection, we see that it is the known emotions that are superimposed. Emotions are what they are, and they exist in the same way in each of us, whether we recognize them for what they are or not. But as our history blends into a new emerging state of the world, a whole new range of emotional responses are triggered within us. An infinite maelstrom of variations generated from a simple combination of a few emotions.

metadata.name: KONSTRUKTS #52
metadata.description:
A study of building and destroying. I built this. You may knock it over.

Humans are both creators and destroyers. One of the earliest games children learn to play is building with blocks, then knocking them down. This simple activity is teaching kids about gravity, cause and effect, and imposing their will on the world around them. As children grow older, the gap between these opposing actions widens. The intention behind knocking things down becomes less innocent, and creators aren't as excited to see their work destroyed.

In 1915, the Russian avant-garde founded the abstract art movement known as Constructivism, rejecting everything except for the absolute purest aspects of form and material. This art was used in service of the Russian revolution and utilized heavily in its propaganda, intended to highlight the utilitarian nature of industrial progress. Mainly, building the new Russia. Its influence is lasting, and can be seen throughout art and design trends even today.

When Russia invaded Ukraine in February of 2022, footage of missiles and airstrikes decimating Ukrainian buildings permeated the media. Ukrainian lives, kitchens, windowsill gardens, and family photos tumbled to the ground. Like children's blocks. Things that took a lifetime to build were destroyed in seconds. 

KONSTRUKTS represents this duality in creation and destruction. Stacked children's blocks are rendered in the style of Constructivist designs like El Lissitzky's Proun series, and Alexander Rodchenko's posters. With a simple tap, blocks (or buildings) can be knocked to the ground.

- Tap anywhere to reveal the KONSTRUKTS menu in the top left. Tap the menu for several options.
- KONSTRUKTS can be exported as USDZ or GLTF models to be used in augmented reality or the metaverse.
- Export a full resolution PNG image from the menu.
- If you knocked over the blocks, you can reset them from the menu.

KONSTRUKTS is built entirely with code, using Three.js, JavaScript, and GLSL.

metadata.name: scratches & circles #68
metadata.description:
first fully coded generative artwork by @ndru_art made with p5.js

project features:
- up to 5 rows of 'scratches' at varying canvas heights & thickness
- scratches generated with random horizontal density and variance
- circles of varying sizes generated within a certain proximity of each row
- 5 different color palettes
- 'narrow scratches' feature defined by rows with a thickness value < 10

minters get 10% of secondary sales

special thanks to Orr Kislev for making his 'sketchy lines' code publicly available

metadata.name: Acid Warning #34
metadata.description:
Acid Warning is an algorithm that generates LSD warning labels.  When Bear and his students were setting up their Richmond acid lab they commissioned this series of warning label designs for their equipment.

The artwork was abandoned as the chemists quickly found it impossible to avoid getting high while working in the lab. Instead of labeling their laboratory gear, they all embraced the ‚ÄúAcid Makers‚Äô Queasy‚Äù for weeks on end.  This generative psychedelia project is a reprint of the Bear‚Äôs lost Acid Warning series.    

- Double click to enable turntable mode
- Click and drag and zoom to move around in 3D
- Don‚Äôt take too much acid in real life homies!

Created by @capnganj - one love <3
